## A multi-dimensional array of numbers

The core data structure of ML. Rank-0 is a scalar, rank-1 a vector, rank-2 a matrix; higher ranks add axes. A tensor is described by its **shape** (size of each axis) and **dtype** (element type).

{#0F766E}Almost every ML operation is a transformation of tensors into other tensors.{/}

## Layers of weighted sums + non-linearities

Each layer computes a weighted sum of its inputs, then applies a non-linear **activation**. Weights and biases are learned from data by minimizing a **loss**.

{#0F766E}Non-linear activations are what let a deep network model relationships a single linear layer never could.{/}

## The learnable weights of the network

**7B** = 7 billion parameters. Parameter count is the headline measure of model size and roughly tracks memory footprint and compute cost.

{#0F766E}At fp16, raw weights take ~2 bytes each — a 7B model is ~14 GB before any activations or KV-cache.{/}

## A dense vector representing an item

Maps a token, word, or image into a continuous space where **similar items sit close together** — turning discrete symbols into vectors a network can compute on.

{#0F766E}Semantic search and RAG rely on comparing embedding vectors by cosine distance.{/}

## The unit a model reads and generates

A chunk of text — often a sub-word — produced by a **tokenizer**. Context limits, pricing, and throughput are all measured in tokens.

{#0F766E}A rough rule of thumb in English: ~1 token ≈ 4 characters ≈ 0.75 words.{/}

## A setting chosen before training

Unlike weights, hyperparameters are **not learned** — you pick them: learning rate, batch size, layer count, hidden dimension.

{#0F766E}Distinction that matters: parameters are learned by the model; hyperparameters are chosen by you.{/}

## Memorizing the training set, not generalizing

The model fits training noise and does poorly on unseen data. **Tell-tale sign:** training loss falls while validation loss climbs.

{#0F766E}Fixes: more data, regularization, dropout, and early stopping.{/}

## Thousands of cores for parallel math

Neural nets are mostly **matrix multiplies**, which map perfectly onto a GPU's massively parallel design — so GPUs are the workhorse of training and inference.

{#0F766E}CPUs optimize for low latency on a few threads; GPUs optimize for throughput across thousands.{/}

## A function that runs on the GPU

Launched in parallel across many threads. Hand-written or compiler-generated kernels for matmul, attention, and normalization are where much of ML performance lives.

{#0F766E}Writing portable, high-performance GPU kernels is a core motivation for Mojo and the Modular stack.{/}

## Single Instruction, Multiple Data

One instruction processes a **whole vector** of values at once — the hardware parallelism behind fast numeric code on CPUs and GPUs.

{#0F766E}In Mojo, `SIMD` is a first-class type, so vectorization is explicit rather than left to luck.{/}

## How fully the GPU's schedulers are kept busy

The ratio of active **warps** to the maximum a streaming multiprocessor can host. More occupancy helps hide memory latency by always having ready work.

{#0F766E}Higher occupancy isn't automatically faster — register and shared-memory pressure can make a lower-occupancy kernel win.{/}

## Low precision for speed, fp32 where it matters

Most matmuls run in **fp16/bf16** for speed and smaller memory; a few stability-critical pieces stay in **fp32**.

{#0F766E}bf16 keeps fp32's exponent range, so it avoids much of fp16's overflow/underflow pain.{/}

## Representing weights in fewer bits

Use **int8 or int4** instead of fp16/fp32 to cut memory and bandwidth and speed up inference — trading a little accuracy.

{#0F766E}Quantization is what lets a 70B-class model run on a single consumer GPU.{/}

## Merge ops into one kernel to avoid memory traffic

Keeps intermediates in fast registers/shared memory instead of writing them out to slow global memory between steps.

{#0F766E}Fusion attacks the memory-bound bottleneck directly — fewer trips to DRAM, more useful work per byte moved.{/}

## The architecture behind modern LLMs

From *Attention Is All You Need* (2017). Stacks of **self-attention** + feed-forward layers process a whole sequence in parallel, replacing RNN-style recurrence.

{#0F766E}Parallel processing of the full sequence is exactly what made transformers scale on GPUs.{/}

## Each token weighs every other token

Uses **query, key, value** vectors: a token's query is matched against all keys to decide how much of each value to pull in.

{#0F766E}Attention captures long-range dependencies directly — distance in the sequence doesn't dilute the signal.{/}

## Several attention heads in parallel

Each head has its own learned projections and can specialize — syntax, position, coreference — and their outputs are concatenated.

{#0F766E}Multiple heads let one layer attend to several relationship types at once.{/}

## Many experts, only a few active per token

A **router** picks a small subset of expert sub-networks for each token, so total parameters can be huge while per-token compute stays modest.

{#0F766E}MoE decouples model capacity from per-token cost — big where it counts, sparse where it doesn't.{/}

## The max tokens a model can see at once

Covers the prompt **plus** the generated output. Bigger windows allow more input but cost more memory and compute.

{#0F766E}Naive attention cost grows with the square of sequence length — long context is expensive.{/}

## Recurrent Neural Network — sequential, stateful

Processes one step at a time, threading a hidden state forward. That recurrence limits parallelism and long-range memory.

{#0F766E}Transformers replaced RNNs largely because parallel attention trains far better on GPUs.{/}

## Gradients via the chain rule, backward

Propagates the loss's gradient back through every layer, giving the partial derivative for each parameter so an optimizer can update it.

{#0F766E}No backprop at inference time — it only runs while training.{/}

## Step downhill on the loss surface

Repeatedly move parameters along the **negative gradient** to reduce loss. The **learning rate** is the step size.

{#0F766E}Too-high learning rate diverges; too-low crawls — it's the single most tuned hyperparameter.{/}

## Cached keys & values for past tokens

During generation the model reuses earlier tokens' **K** and **V** vectors instead of recomputing them every step.

{#0F766E}The KV-cache is a top driver of inference memory use — it grows with both context length and batch size.{/}

## Retrieve documents, then generate

Fetches relevant text via embedding similarity and puts it into the prompt, so answers draw on **external, current** knowledge rather than weights alone.

{#0F766E}RAG reduces hallucination and lets you update knowledge without retraining the model.{/}

## Specialize a pre-trained model on new data

Keep the pre-trained weights and train further on a focused dataset to adapt behavior or domain.

{#0F766E}Parameter-efficient methods like LoRA train tiny adapter weights, so fine-tuning fits on modest hardware.{/}

## Confident output that is simply wrong

The model optimizes for *plausible* next tokens, not verified facts — so it can fabricate fluently.

{#0F766E}Grounding the model with retrieved sources (RAG) is the most common mitigation.{/}

## The matrix-multiply kernel — the heart of ML compute

**GEMM** = General Matrix Multiply: `C = αAB + βC`. Dense layers and attention reduce to matmuls, so this one kernel dominates GPU time.

{#0F766E}Fast matmul is the canonical kernel-optimization problem — tiling, tensor cores, and fusion all aim at it.{/}

## A filter sliding over a 2D feature map

The core op of CNNs: a learned **kernel/filter** sweeps across an image, summing a weighted patch at each position.

{#0F766E}On GPUs conv2d is typically turned into a matmul (im2col or *implicit GEMM*) to reuse the fastest paths.{/}

## NVIDIA's template library for fast GEMM kernels

C++ building blocks for high-performance **matmul and convolution** on CUDA, including tensor cores — it codifies the tiling/pipelining tricks of hand-tuned kernels.

{#0F766E}Mojo's kernel design took inspiration from CUTLASS, expressing the same patterns in MLIR.{/}

## NVIDIA's virtual ISA for the GPU

**P**arallel **T**hread e**X**ecution: a stable, machine-independent assembly that compilers emit, then `ptxas` lowers to the real per-GPU code (**SASS**).

{#0F766E}PTX is portable across GPU generations; SASS is not — that's why PTX exists as the intermediate layer.{/}

## Multi-Level Intermediate Representation

LLVM-family compiler infrastructure for **extensible IRs at multiple abstraction levels**, mixing high-level and hardware-specific dialects in one pipeline.

{#0F766E}Mojo is the first language built from the ground up on MLIR — that foundation is how it spans CPUs, GPUs, and accelerators.{/}

## Work in cache-sized blocks to reuse data

Break the problem into **tiles** that fit in registers / shared memory, so each loaded value is reused many times before leaving fast memory.

{#0F766E}Tiling is the key to fast matmul — it turns a memory-bound loop into a compute-bound one.{/}

## The compiler fuses ops into one kernel for you

Automatic operator fusion: the graph compiler merges adjacent ops so intermediates stay on-chip instead of touching global memory — no hand-written fused kernel needed.

{#0F766E}MAX's graph compiler reflects over Mojo kernels' MLIR to fuse them automatically — a headline win for memory-bound workloads.{/}

## High Bandwidth Memory — the GPU's main DRAM

Stacked DRAM beside the GPU die serving as **global memory**: enormous bandwidth (TB/s) but slow relative to on-chip storage.

{#0F766E}Memory-bound kernels are bottlenecked on HBM traffic — fusion and tiling exist mainly to cut it.{/}

## The fastest, per-thread on-chip storage

Private to each thread and physically in the SM — kernels keep hot values here to dodge slower memory.

{#0F766E}Registers are finite: heavy register use per thread caps how many threads fit, lowering occupancy.{/}

## The smallest unit of GPU execution

One instance of the kernel, with its own registers and index — usually responsible for a single element or small slice of the data.

{#0F766E}You write the code for one thread; the GPU runs thousands of copies in parallel.{/}

## 32 threads executing in lockstep

The GPU's real scheduling unit: a warp's threads run the **same instruction together** (SIMT).

{#0F766E}Branch **divergence** within a warp serializes the paths — keep threads in a warp on the same control flow.{/}

## A cooperating group of threads on one SM

Threads in a block share **shared memory** and can synchronize at a **barrier** — it's the level where threads cooperate, e.g. loading a tile together.

{#0F766E}Shared memory and barriers only work *within* a block; across blocks there's no such guarantee.{/}

## All the blocks of one kernel launch

The top of the hierarchy: **thread → warp → block → grid**. You pick grid and block dimensions to map threads across the whole problem.

{#0F766E}The grid is logical — its blocks are scheduled onto SMs as they free up, so it can be far larger than the GPU.{/}

## Rows laid out contiguously in memory

Elements of a row sit next to each other (C/NumPy default); **column-major** (Fortran/BLAS) stores columns instead.

{#0F766E}Layout decides which accesses are coalesced — matching your loop order to the layout is a core perf concern.{/}

## A wait-for-everyone point within a block

Every thread in the block must reach the barrier before any continues — the way to safely coordinate **shared memory**.

{#0F766E}Classic pattern: write a tile to shared memory, hit a barrier, then everyone reads it.{/}

## Same op on every element, independently

**Use for:** activations (ReLU, GELU), adds, scaling, casts. Embarrassingly parallel, one thread per element.

{#0F766E}Almost always memory-bound — which is exactly why these get fused into neighboring kernels.{/}

## Collapse many values into few along an axis

**Use for:** sum, max, mean, L2-norm. Needs threads to combine partials via **tree reductions / warp shuffles / shared memory**.

{#0F766E}The classic parallel-cooperation kernel — unlike elementwise, threads must talk to each other.{/}

## Running aggregate over a sequence

**Use for:** cumulative sum, stream compaction, sorting, allocation offsets. Each output folds in everything before it.

{#0F766E}Looks inherently serial but parallel-scan algorithms make it fast — a staple GPU primitive.{/}

## Reorder a tensor's axes (swap rows/columns)

**Use for:** changing layout to feed the next op (e.g. matmul) efficiently.

{#0F766E}Pure data movement, but a textbook case for **shared-memory tiling** — the naive version wrecks coalescing.{/}

## softmax(QKᵀ / √dₖ) · V

Score each query against every key, scale by **√dₖ**, softmax into weights, then weight-sum the values.

{#0F766E}The naive kernel materializes the full N×N score matrix — O(N²) memory and compute in sequence length.{/}

## Fused, IO-aware attention — no N×N matrix in HBM

Tiles Q/K/V into blocks and runs an **online softmax** (streaming running max + sum) entirely in on-chip SRAM.

{#0F766E}Drops attention memory from O(N²) to O(N) and makes it compute-bound — the kernel behind long-context transformers.{/}

## Attention over a paged, non-contiguous KV-cache

Reads keys/values from fixed-size **pages** via a block table — like OS virtual memory — instead of one contiguous buffer per sequence.

{#0F766E}Pioneered by vLLM (PagedAttention): kills KV-cache fragmentation so a server fits many more concurrent requests.{/}

## Rotate Q/K dimension-pairs by position

Encodes position by rotating pairs of dims of **query and key** by a position-dependent angle — relative position then drops out of the dot product.

{#0F766E}MAX fuses RoPE with RMSNorm and QKV projection in its MLA attention path.{/}

## Normalize each sample over its features

Zero-mean, unit-variance across the feature axis, then learned **γ scale** and **β shift**. A per-row reduction + elementwise rescale.

{#0F766E}Normalizes per-sample, so it's independent of batch size — unlike BatchNorm.{/}

## LayerNorm without the mean subtraction

Divide each vector by its **root-mean-square**, then apply a learned scale — no centering, no bias.

{#0F766E}One reduction instead of two: cheaper than LayerNorm, which is why Llama-class models use it.{/}

## Many independent matmuls in one launch

Runs a GEMM per batch entry / per attention head together, amortizing launch overhead and keeping the GPU busy.

{#0F766E}Attention is built on batched matmul: one QKᵀ and one score·V per head.{/}

## Many differently-shaped matmuls, one launch

Schedules tiles from GEMMs of **varying shapes** together — unlike batched matmul, the shapes can differ.

{#0F766E}The MoE workhorse: one GEMM per expert over its routed tokens, fused so no expert stalls the GPU.{/}

## Matrix × vector — the batch-1 matmul

Little to no data reuse, so it's **memory-bandwidth-bound**, not compute-bound.

{#0F766E}One-token-at-a-time decoding makes every layer a GEMV — the root cause of memory-bound LLM inference.{/}

## Unroll conv patches so it becomes a matmul

Lays each receptive field out as a matrix column, turning convolution into one **GEMM** against the reshaped filters.

{#0F766E}*Implicit GEMM* does the same mapping on the fly — no expanded matrix in memory.{/}

## Fewer multiplies for small-filter conv

Transform-based fast convolution (e.g. 3×3): trades expensive **multiplications** for cheaper additions.

{#0F766E}Speeds up compute-bound CNN layers — but adds transform overhead and a bit more numerical error.{/}

## Downsample a feature map by windows

Slide a window, emit one value each: **max-pool** (maximum) or **avg-pool** (mean). No learned weights.

{#0F766E}A windowed reduction — memory-bound — that shrinks resolution and adds slight translation invariance.{/}

## Gather rows of the embedding table by token ID

The first op in an LLM: index integer IDs into the embedding matrix to fetch their vectors.

{#0F766E}Equivalent to *one-hot × table*, but done as a **gather** — never materialize the one-hot matmul.{/}

## Convert a tensor's numeric type

Elementwise fp32↔bf16, fp16↔fp32, int↔float — the casts mixed-precision inserts around low-precision matmuls.

{#0F766E}Trivial math, pure data movement: memory-bound, so fuse it into a neighbor rather than launch it alone.{/}

## Bias + activation folded into the matmul's tail

Applies bias / activation / scale / cast to each output tile **while it's still in registers**, before the write-out.

{#0F766E}Saves a full HBM round-trip versus separate kernels — the canonical fusion in a GEMM epilogue.{/}

## Randomly zero elements during training

Drops each element with probability **p**, scales survivors by **1/(1−p)** to preserve the mean.

{#0F766E}Regularizes the network; needs a fast per-element RNG — and is disabled at inference.{/}
